Brett,
A couple things to think about:
1)	 I would recommend we stay on the same course for SRED that
 we have taken for years. We have to say this is P2PE comparable
 until the full program is done. Even though we are using all the same
 components and listing, P2PE has a whole reporting and process section
 that we aren't able to do just yet. Let's not overstep so the QSA
 can do their job.
2)	 If the merchant wants us to be the integrator, then the listing would
 also need our integration guide. Using a certified P2PE solution is
 not a free past to escape PCI. The merchant still needs to use a
 certified integrator and follow the guide, otherwise, they break the
 chain of custody.

Subject: RE: Databreach

We are aware of the issues at hand and will come up with a letter. See below:

Merchants on the Cayan platform have been compromised with malware that was installed on their systems through Cayan's support
tools. This matter is under investigation by the U.S. Secret Service.

At a high level, this impacts merchants who use Cayan's Genius CED (countertop) or Genius Handheld (mobile) devices where Cayan's
support/remote access software was used. It appears that Cayan's software had a vulnerability that allowed hackers to install malware
on the devices and capture card data. These devices are P2PE-validated, but that alone doesn't mean that merchants are exempt from
compromise. P2PE protects data while it is being transmitted, but this malware issue exploited a vulnerability outside of the general data
flow. It's worth mentioning that merchants may be liable for a data breach even if the solution they use is P2PE-validated.

I have spoken with the Secret Service multiple times this week and they are stating that the breach originated from Cayan
technicians' computers where they used remote support software that they installed on the Genius devices.
